$m2 = random(11,49,2);
$b2 = random(0.2,0.9,0.1);
$a2 = random(12,28,2);
$ans2 = Compute("ln($m2/$a2) / ln($b2)");

BEGIN_TEXT

Find the exact solution to the exponential equation \( $m2 = $a2( $b2 )^q \).  ${BITALIC}(Do not give a decimal approximation.)${EITALIC}
$BR
$BR
\( q = \) \{ ans_rule(25) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("logarithms") \}

END_TEXT

ANS($ans2->cmp(tolType=>'absolute',tolerance=>'0.000000000001') );

#ANS(num_cmp( $ans2,tol=>0.000000000001 ) );

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
We begin by dividing both sides by $a2 to isolate the exponent: $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \frac{$m2}{$a2} = ($b2)^{q} \).
$BR
Now we are solving for an exponent, so we use logarithms.  We can use either the common logarithm or the natural logarithm.  Using the log rules, we have $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ ($b2)^q = \frac{$m2}{$a2} \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \log{ \left( $b2^q \right)} = \log{ \left( \frac{$m2}{$a2} \right)} \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ q \log{$b2} = \log{ \left( \frac{$m2}{$a2} \right)} \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \displaystyle q = \frac{\log{\left( \frac{$m2}{$a2} \right) }}{\log{$b2}} \). $BR
Note that if you used the natural log instead, your answer would be \( \ q = \frac{\ln{\left( \frac{$m2}{$a2} \right) }}{\ln{$b2}} \) which is equivalent to the answer obtained using the common log.
$BR
END_SOLUTION



